05004nam a22007215i 9780226571539DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020019260  a97802265715397 a10.7208/97802265715392doi  a(DE-B1597)571684  a(OCoLC)1224278835  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aKF3841b.B73 2020 4aKF3841 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a346.7304qLOC1 aBradshaw, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWildlife as Property Owners :bA New Conception of Animal Rights /cKaren Bradshaw. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I A Foundational Understanding of Animal Property Law -- t1 The Nexus of Animal Rights and the Rights of Nature -- t2 Biodiversity Loss as a Property Law Problem -- tPart II Revealing the Existing Body of Animal Property Rights -- t3 The Biological Origins of Property -- t4 Uncovering Animal Rights in Existing Property Law -- tPart III A Roadmap for Property Ownership to Benefit Biodiversity -- t5 Using Legal Trusts to Implement a System of Animal Property Rights -- t6 Traditional Legal Pathways to Formalizing Animal Property Rights -- t7 Leveraging Property Rights to Aid Biodiversity -- t8 Case Studies of Stakeholder Collaborations Managing Resource Competition between Humans and Wildlife -- tPart IV Analyzing the Potential of Animal Property Ownership -- t9 Evaluating a Property-Based Approach to Biodiversity Preservation -- t10 The Implications of Interspecies Ownership on Property Theory -- tConclusion: Are Animal Property Rights the Rights of Nature? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHumankind coexists with every other living thing. People drink the same water, breathe the same air, and share the same land as other animals. Yet, property law reflects a general assumption that only people can own land. The effects of this presumption are disastrous for wildlife and humans alike. The alarm bells ringing about biodiversity loss are growing louder, and the possibility of mass extinction is real. Anthropocentric property is a key driver of biodiversity loss, a silent killer of species worldwide. But as law and sustainability scholar Karen Bradshaw shows, if excluding animals from a legal right to own land is causing their destruction, extending the legal right to own property to wildlife may prove its salvation. Wildlife as Property Owners advocates for folding animals into our existing system of property law, giving them the opportunity to own land just as humans do—to the betterment of all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnimal diversityzUnited States. 0aAnimal rightszUnited States. 0aAnimalsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszUnited States. 0aLand tenurezUnited States. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 0aRight of propertyzUnited States. 0aRights of naturezUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aanimal law.  aanimal rights.  abiodiversity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishz978311070486008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020z9783110704587oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226571539423Coveruhttps://www